[White "Budapest Gambit - Theory"]
[Black "Get it Fast! A Brief Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 Ng4 4. e3 { Forcing the knight to move. } 4... Nxe5
{ 4...Bb4+  5.Bd2 !  Bxd2+  6.Qxd2  Nxe5  7.f4 !  and the plan is very easy.  Nec6  8.g3 !  Kasparov's set up.   4...h5 ?!  5.f4 !  Bc5  6.Qf3  ± }
5. f4 { The main point. We should avoid ...d6 allowing the knight to d7. } 5...
Ng6
{ 5...Nec6  6.Nf3 !  Now Black should decide how to play.  g6   6...Bb4+  7.Bd2  Qe7  8.Kf2 !  O-O  9.Bxb4  Qxb4  10.Qc2  Qc5  11.Nc3  d6  12.Bd3  h6  13.a3  +=   6...Bc5  7.Bd3  O-O  8.Nc3  d6  9.a3  a5  10.Bd2  h6  11.Qe2 !  ±  Kramnik's set up.  7.Bd2 !  Like this we make use of the weaknesses on the kingside.  Bg7  8.Bc3  O-O  9.Bxg7  Kxg7  10.Nc3  +=   5...Bb4+  6.Bd2 !  Bxd2+  7.Qxd2  Nec6  8.Nc3  += }
6. Nc3
{ The most accurate move. Before developing our bishop to d3, it is very important to take control of the d5 square. }
6... Bc5 { 6...Bb4  7.Nge2  O-O  8.a3  Bxc3+  9.Nxc3  ± } 7. Bd3 d6 8. Nge2
{ If I play the knight to f3, Black will play ...Nh4 exchanging the knights. Moreover, there are tricks with ...Nxf4 if we castle. We can call this Salgado's set up. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Re8 { 9...a5  10.Bd2  Nd7  11.Qc2  Re8  12.Ng3  += } 10. Bc2
{ We postpone deciding where to place the knights and leave the square d3 for the queen. }
10... Bxe3+
{ 10...Nd7  11.Ne4 !  Bb6  12.N2c3  Placing the knights like this is very typical.  Ne7  13.Qh5  g6  14.Qe2  +=  And Black's position has holes on the dark squares. }
11. Bxe3 Rxe3 12. Qd2 Re8 13. f5 Ne5 14. f6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Budapest Gambit - Theory"]
[Black "Budapest Gambit: Knight to c6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 Ng4 4. e3
{ Now Black has several options but only one is reasonable. } 4... Nxe5
{ 4...h5 ?!  Defending the knight like this is not so good.  5.f4 !  Bc5  6.Qf3  ±  Here we see the difference. The diagonal g1-a7 is not weakened !   4...Bb4+  Trying first to exchange the bishop and then castle as soon as possible.  5.Bd2  Bxd2+  6.Qxd2 !  Better to recapture with the queen. Our knight belongs to c3 to control d5.  Nxe5  7.f4 !  and we will get similar positions to the ones we will see later. }
5. f4
{ There are almost no games with this move  (I don't like to count myself !)  . I could find only some correspondence games, but not a single GM has tried it ! The point is very easy: I want Black to commit the knight, first. Once the knight is played to g6 or c6, I can plan how to place my pieces accordingly. Hence, this is the most flexible way of playing. One important point to note is that the best square for the Black knight is c5, because from there he can attack the weakest point in White's position, the e4 square. We will always be very careful not to allow that. }
5... Nec6
{ 5...Bb4+  6.Bd2 !  Bxd2+  7.Qxd2  Nec6  8.g3 !  I like this move very much, playing like Kasparov. We place our bishop in the best diagonal, protect our weakest square and we avoid the possible breakthrough, d5, which would allow Black to liberate the position.  O-O  9.Bg2  Re8  10.Nc3  d6  11.Nge2  +=  Here every Grandmaster would finish their analysis with a positive evaluation for White, and that White's position is much easier to play. But this is not enough for me. In the Understand it chapter we will try to figure out how to play this position and lay out all the possible ideas for both colours. }
6. Nf3
{ This way of playing is the most active and the one I like the most. Anyway, I have a recipe for extremely positional and lazy people !   6.g3 !?  Trying to play like Gary once again.  Bc5 !  If there is a problem, this is it. The point is that the pressure on e3 is a bit annoying. I like Kasparov's set up much more when the Black squared bishops are exchanged.   6...Bb4+  7.Bd2  Qe7 !  Trying to annoy White's coordination.  8.Kf2 !  We will find this move in the Budapest several times. We lose the right to castle but the king has no problems at all.  O-O  9.Bg2  Re8  10.Nf3   10.Ne2 ?!  Bc5 !  11.Qc1  Nb4 !  and some threats are coming !  10...Na6  11.Re1  Nc5  12.Kg1  and according to the computer, White is slightly better, although not as much as I would like !  7.Bg2  O-O  8.Nf3 !   8.Ne2 ?!  Re8 !  Again, the pressure on e3 doesn't allow us to develop our knight to e2.  9.Nbc3 !?  Bxe3  10.Bxe3  Rxe3  11.Nd5  Re8  But in this case, White doesn't have enough compensation.  8...Re8  9.O-O !  d6   9...Bxe3+ ?  here we have an idea !  10.Bxe3  Rxe3  11.Ng5 !  (Qh5 is coming !)  h6  12.Ne4  and the rook is trapped ! We will take the exchange with winning position.  10.Ng5 !?  h6  11.Ne4  Bb6  12.Nbc3  and White seems to be slightly better once again, although I get the feeling that, with g3, we didn't get the maximum from the position. }
6... Bc5
{ This is always the most logical way.   6...Bb4+  7.Bd2 !   7.Kf2 !?  is interesting here as well.  7...Qe7  8.Kf2  I like this move order a bit more because now the queen is on e7. Maybe we will manage to gain a tempo with Nd5 in the future.  Bxd2   8...O-O ?!  9.Bxb4  Now the Black pieces are misplaced.  Qxb4   9...Nxb4  10.a3  N4c6  11.Nc3  d6  12.Bd3  ±  All the White pieces are on the best squares.  10.Qc2  Qc5  11.Nc3  d6  12.Bd3  h6  13.a3  +=  It is important to remember this position. White's pieces are perfectly placed.  9.Qxd2  Na6  10.Nc3  Nc5  11.g3 !  Again, we play like Kasparov.  O-O  12.Bg2  d6  13.Nd4  +=   6...g6  Trying to get the bishop onto the long diagonal. We should fight this.  7.Bd2 !  A very important move. Now we will get the same as in the ...Bb4 variations, and the pawn on g6 will leave a hole on f6.  Bg7  8.Bc3  O-O  9.Bxg7  Kxg7  10.Nc3  += }
7. Bd3 { My favourite set up, with the idea of mating Black in the future. }
7... O-O
{ 7...Nb4 ?!  8.Be2  and at some point we can follow with a3 and b4.   7...a5  8.Nc3  d6  9.Bd2  nothing changes.   7...d5  8.cxd5  Qxd5  9.Nc3 !  We get many tempi.  Qd8  10.a3  following Qc2 or b4-Bb2 at the right moment. White is much better. }
8. Nc3
{ 8.Bxh7+ !?  This is an interesting try, but I couldn't manage to make it work.  Kxh7  9.Ng5+  Kg6 !  10.Nc3  d5 !  The lines are really complicated. Probably White is slighty better, but we don't need to examine the details here. }
8... d6 9. a3
{ I like this move: Nb4 is not possible anymore, and at the right moment we can play b4. }
9... a5 10. Bd2
{ Completing development and not showing our cards about our king. Are we going to the kingside or to the queenside ? }
10... h6
{ It's important to play this move. The sacrifice on h7 would come at some point ! }
11. Qe2
{ The computer gives a very big advantage for White, and not without reason. All the pieces are developed and only the king needs to move. Thanks to our attacking ideas with Bxh7 Black was forced to play h6, and there will consequently be a hook on g5 for our g pawn. We will check this position more deeply in the Understand it chapter. I don't want you to get this position and get lost afterwards ! }
*

