1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 Ng4 4. e3
{ Now Black has several options but only one is reasonable. } 4... Nxe5 5. f4
{ There are almost no games with this move  (I don't like to count myself !)  . I could find only some correspondence games, but not a single GM has tried it ! The point is very easy: I want Black to commit the knight, first. Once the knight is played to g6 or c6, I can plan how to place my pieces accordingly. Hence, this is the most flexible way of playing. One important point to note is that the best square for the Black knight is c5, because from there he can attack the weakest point in White's position, the e4 square. We will always be very careful not to allow that. }
5... Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Nec6 8. g3
{ I like this move very much, playing like Kasparov. We place our bishop in the best diagonal, protect our weakest square and we avoid the possible breakthrough, d5, which would allow Black to liberate the position. }
8... O-O 9. Bg2 Re8 10. Nc3 d6 11. Nge2
{ Here every Grandmaster would finish their analysis with a positive evaluation for White, and that White's position is much easier to play. But this is not enough for me. In the Understand it chapter we will try to figure out how to play this position and lay out all the possible ideas for both colours. }
