[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Blumenfeld Gambit - Theory"]
[Black "6...a6 and 7...d5: Modern System"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 b5 5. dxe6 fxe6 6. cxb5 a6 7. e3 d5 8. Nc3
{ We will follow Karpov-Edouard, but now we will go deeper into some variations. }
8... Be7
{ A very interesting move for Black. Once the Knight is on c3 it is impossible to play e4 because Black can play ...d4 with tempo. Given this, Black has a free hand to attack on the kingside. This is probably the best variation for Black in the whole system, but I didn't realise this until I decided to write this book. So it's fair to assume that other people won't realise this either.   8...Bd6 ?!  9.e4 !   8...c4  9.bxa6  Nxa6  10.Be2 !  Nc5 !?  Probably the most annoying move.   10...Bb4  11.Bd2  O-O  12.O-O  Nc5  13.Qc2  We have already seen this, and nothing else needs to be said. Karpov, A  (2623)  - Edouard, R  (2659)  Cap d'Agde 2014.  11.O-O  Bd6   11...Be7  12.Nd4  Bd7  13.b3 !  +=  12.Nb5 !  Bb8  13.Bd2 !  White develops all the pieces.  Qd7   13...O-O ?!  14.Bb4 !  Nfe4  15.b3 !  We have managed to break the pawn chain, with advantage.  14.a4 !  Nb3  15.Ra3  Nxd2  16.Qxd2  Qe7   16...O-O !?  17.b3 !  Once again, this move is important.  cxb3  18.Rxb3  Rxa4  19.Nbd4  Ra8  20.Bb5  and White is better because of the control of the c-file and the c6 square. The pawn on e6 will likely become a target for White to attack, in the future.  17.b3 !  N  The easiest move for White.   17.Ra2  Bd7  18.Nc3  O-O  19.a5  Kh8  20.g3  Bd6  was not so clear in Baciak, M  (2183)  - Pavlicek, M  (2292)  ICCF email 2015.  17...Bd7  18.Raa1  cxb3  19.Rfb1  and White is better because of the passed pawn. }
9. b3
{ 9.Be2  O-O  10.O-O  axb5  11.Bxb5  Bb7  Black has good play. The Knight on c3 is misplaced, as you already know. }
9... O-O 10. a4
{ We should learn from the Russian Grandmaster, Volkov, who has shown some interesting ideas, here. This move looks safer than the main line because we can always play Bd2 against Qa5 ideas. Anyway, it is important to understand the point behind 10. Bb2.   10.Bb2  Qa5   10...axb5 !?  A very concrete line appears.  11.Bxb5  Qa5  12.Bd3  d4 !?   12...Nc6  13.O-O  following Ne2, Black doesn't have enough compensation.  13.exd4  cxd4  14.Nxd4  Ba3 !?  15.Qd2  Qe5+  16.Nde2  Bxb2  17.Qxb2  Ng4  Black has sacrificed everything to obtain the initiative. But was it enough ?  18.f3 !  N  White was afraid of the Knight on e3, but nothing dramatic happens.   18.Qc2 ?  Bb7  19.Bxh7+  Kh8  20.Be4  Nc6 !  and Black is three pawns down but so active that he is almost winning ! Dautov, R  (2535)  - Blees, A  (2355)  Kecskemet 1989.  18...Ne3  19.Be4  Nxg2+  20.Kf2  +-  11.Qc2 !   11.Qd2 ?  axb5  12.Nxb5  Qb6 !  13.Nc3  According to my database, the players agreed to a draw in Dokutchaev, A  (2442)  - Nyback, T  (2599)  Finland 2013, but after  Nc6  14.Be2  d4  15.Nb5  Ba6  16.a4  c4 !  it is White who seems to be in big trouble !  11...axb5  12.Bxb5  Bb7  13.Be2 !   13.O-O ?!  d4  14.exd4  Bxf3  15.gxf3  cxd4  White loses a piece.  13...Nc6  14.O-O  d4  15.exd4   15.Na4  Nb4  16.Qc1  d3  looks a bit scary, although after  17.Bd1  Ne4  18.Ne5  White may not be worse.  15...Nxd4  16.Nxd4  cxd4  17.Nb5  Rac8  18.Qd1  e5  Black has compensation for the pawn. White's pieces are not really active. }
10... Bb7 11. Be2 axb5 { 11...Qa5  12.Bd2 ! } 12. Nxb5 Ne4
{ This is the only way for Black to prove some initiative. } 13. O-O Bf6 14.
Rb1 Na6 15. Nd2
{ White made normal moves and now decides to fight against the centralized Knight. }
15... Ng5 16. Ba3
{ Followed by Rc1, and White is much better. If Black plays 16... e5 then 17. e4 ! would follow, with the better position.   16.f4 !?  typical, but not the best.  Nf7  17.Nf3  Qe7 !  18.Bd2 ?!   18.Ba3  is more logical.  18...e5  19.fxe5  Nxe5  20.h3  Rae8  Black got some compensation, but eventually lost in Volkov, S  (2607)  - Stopa, J  (2460)  Rasht 2016. }
