[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Tarrasch and Marshall Gambits"]
[Black "Marshall Gambit: 6.d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. e4
{ Frank Marshall played this gambit many times and with very good results. Later, Grandmasters like Bronstein, Knaak, and Mamedyarov would do the same. It's not very dangerous, but Black needs to know exactly how to answer it. }
5... dxe4 { Now White has several options, but none give him advantage. } 6. d5
{ Some kind of Albin Gambit.   6.Bc4 !?  and 6. Bb5 will be covered in the following analysis. }
6... Nf6 7. Bg5 Nbd7
{ Very good move. It's strange that no one played like this in the past. } 8.
Qe2
{ The best attempt to fight for compensation.   8.f3  doesn't help White:  Bd6 !  9.fxe4  O-O  Black will later play ...Re8 and will try to gain space on the queenside with ...a6 and ...b5. The e5 square is weak as well. Taken together these factors give Black a very good position.   8.Nxe4  Be7 !  9.Nxf6+  Nxf6  10.Bb5+  Kf8 !  The d5 pawn will fall. }
8... Be7
{ Black wants straightforwardly to complete development.   8...Qa5 !?  9.O-O-O  Be7  This avoids the double pawn sacrifice that we will see later. }
9. d6
{ Interesting second pawn sacrifice, but Black can hold after   9.O-O-O  Qa5 !  10.Nxe4   10.Qb5 !?  Qxb5  11.Bxb5  a6  This is probably the best continuation for White, but such play is hardly what White was planning to do following his opening sacrifices.  10...O-O  11.d6  Bd8 !  ∓  The pawn on d6 is not dangerous at all, and White's King is weak. }
9... Bxd6 10. Nxe4 Be7 11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. O-O-O Bxd6
{ The sharpest try.   12...Ne8 !?  13.Bxe7+  Qxe7  14.Nxe8  Qxe8  15.Qxe8+  Kxe8  16.Nf3  White has enough compensation to fight for equality. }
13. Rxd6 Qa5
{ Risky, but seems to be ok. White still needs time to develop the kingside and cannot create serious threats. }
14. Nf3
{ 14.a3  h6 !  15.Bf4  Kg8  16.Nf3  Nf8 !  The Black King will be safe on h7, and the Bishop will develop to e6. White has compensation, but not enough for an advantage. }
14... h6 15. Bxf6 { 15.Bf4  Qxa2  ∓ } 15... Nxf6 16. Qe5 Bg4
{ Black completes development with ...Re8, so White should play very fast. }
17. Rxf6 { Now a very concrete line appears. } 17... gxf6 18. Qd6+ Kg7 19. Qg3
h5 20. h3 Qxa2 21. Bd3 Rad8 22. hxg4 Rxd3 23. gxh5+ Kh7 24. Ng5+ fxg5 25. Qxd3+
Kh6 26. Qd6+ Qe6 27. Qxe6+ fxe6
{ The position is almost equal, although I still prefer Black. } *

