[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Von Hennig-Schara Gambit - White Repertoire"]
[Black "7...Nf6 8.Qd1 with 10.a3!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6
8. Qd1 Nc6 9. Nf3 Bc5 10. a3
{ I was very surprised when I saw the computer giving this move as the best by far. There is a point behind it, as you will see later. I must confess that this is the only place in the whole Gambit where I found some real advantage for White ! }
10... O-O 11. Bg5
{ The moves a3 and Bg5 seem a bit strange, one after another, but there is a point behind it. If Black plays ...Qb6, at some point, he doesn't really threaten ...Qxb2 because the queen, on b2, would be trapped !   11.Bf4 !?  Another attempt to develop the bishop, and afterwards play e3.  Qb6   11...Qe7  12.e3  Rfd8  13.Qc2  +=  12.e3  Honestly speaking, White is better here, but the moves are not easy to find.  Rfd8   12...Bf5 !?  13.Bb5  Ne4  14.Qe2  Nxc3  15.bxc3  Rad8  16.O-O  a6  17.Bc4  Na5  18.Nd4  Nxc4  19.Qxc4  Be4  Once again White is better, but Black has some compensation.  13.Be2 !  The only reason anyone would play like this, is because they have this book, too !   13.Qb1 ?!  Bf5 !  14.Qa2  Bb4 !?  This is a funny variation, and Black has good compensation   14...Na5  15.b4  Rac8 !  is perhaps even funnier !  13...Bf5   13...Bh3  14.Nd2  Bxg2  15.Rg1  Ne4  16.Rxg2  Nxd2  17.Qc2  ±  14.Qc1 !  Be7   14...Na5 ?  15.Na4 !  +-  15.O-O  Ne4  16.Nxe4  Bxe4  17.Qc4 !  Bd5  18.Qb5  Qxb5  19.Bxb5  a6  20.Bxc6  Bxc6  21.Nd4  Bd7  Black is worse but has some survival chances thanks to the bishop pair.   11.b4 ?!  Bb6  12.e3  Qe7  White has simply created weaknesses on the queenside. }
11... h6
{ 11...Qb6 ?!  12.e3  Be7  13.Bd3  Bg4  14.Qc2  h6  15.Bh4  Rfd8  16.O-O  Bxf3  17.gxf3  ±  1-0  (32)  Wang, Y  (2702)  - Wang, C  (2490)  Xinghua 2012. }
12. Bh4
{ This move seems to be very dangerous, in my opinion. The pawn on b2 is weak, Black has the possibility to gain more tempi with g5 and, who knows, maybe g4 as well. Black's pieces seem to be able to enter the game extremely easily... I thought Black should be ok, somehow, but I couldn't manage to find a reasonable continuation. Given this, we are probably looking at the REFUTATION OF THE GAMBIT.   12.Bxf6 ?!  Qxf6 !  The computer doesn't realize how strong this is ! Now the situation becomes extremely interesting !  13.Qxd7  Rfd8  14.Qg4  N   14.Qh3  Bxa3 !!  Another great move ! This gambit is full of life !  15.Rxa3  Nb4  16.e3  Nc2+  17.Ke2  Nxa3  18.Nd4  Qb6  19.Kf3  Qxb2  20.Nce2  Nc4  =+  Draw  (31)  Bredenhof, B  (2124)  - Andersen, J  (2168)  ICCF email 2011  14...Ne5  15.Qg3  Qb6 !  Black attacks the weaknesses on the queenside.  16.Rb1  But now comes one of the best moves I've seen in my chess career.  Rac8 !!  Black plays according to that principle of attacking chess: get all your pieces into the party. But to do this Black simply leaves his knight on e5 hanging, which is simply amazing !  17.e3   17.Nxe5  Bxa3  18.Nd3  Rxc3  19.e4  Bb4  20.bxc3  Bxc3+  21.Ke2  Qxb1  22.Qe3  a5  ∞  A piece down but the a-pawn is very fast...  17...Bxa3  18.Bb5  Bxb2  19.O-O  Nxf3+  20.Qxf3  Rxc3  21.Rxb2  a6  22.Qe2  axb5  23.Qxb5  Qxb5  24.Rxb5  Rd7  Black has to suffer a little bit, but the endgame is equal. Anyway, the probability that White will make a mistake on the way is extremely high ! }
12... g5 13. Bg3
{ I had the feeling that Black should have something in this position, but I failed to prove it. I could only find one variation where White needs to play extremely accurately to gain some advantage. So, objectively, White is better. }
13... Qb6
{ 13...g4 ?!  14.Nd2  Blacks position hasn't improved and he should now worry about Bh4 ideas, in the future. }
14. e3 { As I said before, the pawn on b2 is untouchable. } 14... Rad8
{ The best practical chance.   14...Bf5 !?  This is very interesting but White has a very strong move.  15.Bc4 !   15.Be2  Rfd8  16.Qc1  Nh5  17.O-O  Nxg3  18.hxg3  Bf8  Black has some compensation, thanks to the bishop pair.  15...Na5   15...Qxb2 ?  16.Na4  +-  16.Na4 !  Qc6  17.Nxc5  Nxc4  18.Qd4  Ne4  19.Nxe4  Qxe4  20.O-O  g4  21.Qxe4  Bxe4  22.Ne5  Nxe5  23.Bxe5  ±  This endgame is not the kind of thing we wanted when choosing to play this gambit...   14...Qxb2 ?  15.Na4 !  +- }
15. Qc1
{ This is not an easy move to make ! White allows ...Na5-Nb3.   15.Qb1 ?  Bf5  16.Bc7   16.Qxf5  Qxb2  16...Qb3 !  17.Qa2  Qxa2  18.Rxa2  Rc8  =∞   15.Bc4 !?  This is quite good.  Na5  16.Na4 !  These kind of moves are not easy ! Now Black has two options.  Bxa4   16...Qc6 !?  17.Nxc5  Nxc4  18.Nxd7  Rxd7  19.Qc2  g4  20.b3 !  gxf3  21.Qxc4  Qxc4  22.bxc4  fxg2  23.Rg1  Re8  24.Rxg2  Kh7  25.Rd1  Re4  Black is close to equality, but will still need to fight.  17.Qxa4  Nxc4  18.Qxc4  Rc8  19.O-O  Bxa3  20.Qa4  Bc5  21.b4  Qxb4  22.Qxb4  Bxb4  23.Rxa7  White is slightly better, but with good play I think that Black can to hold.   15.Qc2 ?  allows  Bf5 ! }
15... Na5 16. b4
{ White has no fear !   16.Qc2 ?!  Bf5  17.Qxf5  Qxb2  18.Be5  It seems as though White is completely winning, but things are not so simple.  Ng4 !!  Great counterattack !   18...Qxa1+ ?  19.Nb1 !  This was White's idea.  19.Ne4 !   19.Qxg4  Qxa1+  -+   19.Ra2  Qc1+  20.Ke2  Nc4  21.Rc2  Ncxe3 !!  There are tactics all over the place !  22.Qxf7+   22.Qxg5+  hxg5  23.Rxc1  Bxa3  24.fxe3  Bxc1  The computer considers the position to be equal, but the game has just started !  22...Rxf7  23.Rxc1  Nxf1  24.Ne4   24.Rhxf1  Nxe5  25.Nxe5  Re8  =+  24...Bxa3  25.Ra1  Nxe5  26.Nxe5  Rf4  27.f3  Bb2  28.Rhxf1  Bxe5  29.Rxa7 =  19...Nxe5  20.Qxe5  Bd4 !  21.Nxd4  Qxa1+  22.Ke2  Nb3  23.Nf6+  Kh8  Luckily, for Black, it seems that mate cannot be delivered.  24.Qf5  Kg7  25.Nh5+  Kg8  26.Kf3 !?  Qd1+  27.Kg3  Nxd4  28.Nf6+  Kg7  29.exd4  Qxd4  The position seems to be more or less balanced. }
16... Nb3
{ 16...Bxe3 ?  17.Qxe3  Rfe8  18.Ne5  Nc6  19.Qxb6  axb6  20.O-O-O  Nxe5  21.Kb2  ± }
17. bxc5 Qxc5
{ 17...Qa5  18.Qb2  Nxa1  19.Qxa1  Ne4  20.Be5 !  This move is the key !   20.Bc7 ?  Qxc3+  21.Qxc3  Nxc3  22.Bxd8  Rxd8 =  20...Rfe8  21.Bd4  Bg4  22.Qb2  Rxd4  23.Nxd4  Qxc3+  24.Qxc3  Nxc3  25.Bd3  Rc8  26.c6 !  bxc6  27.Kd2  ±  Black has too many weaknesses in the endgame and probably won't be able to hold the position. }
18. Qb2 Nxa1 19. Qxa1 Rfe8
{ The position doesn't look so clear. White's king is still in the center and Black will probably have some activity. Unfortunately, for Black, White manages to consolidate. }
20. Qb2
{ An impossible move to find in a practical game, I would say. The idea is to play Qb4 and exchange queens, but you really need to be cold-blooded to play such a move.   20.Be2 ?!  Rc8 !  21.Na2  Ne4  22.O-O  Qxa3  23.Be5  Be6  24.Nc1  Qxa1  25.Bxa1  Nc3  26.Bd3  Bc4 !  And if White doesn't have the bishop pair, I doubt he has an advantage. }
20... Rc8 21. Nd1 Qa5+ 22. Qb4 Qxb4+ 23. axb4 Nd5 24. Nd4 Nxb4 25. h4
{ White has some edge. The pair of bishops will prove strong, at some point. Anyway, Black still has two passed pawns on the queenside, so the position is not without chances for Black. We will need to see practical examples ! }
*

