[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Von Hennig-Schara Gambit - Black Repertoire"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara 5.Qxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ This is not the main line, but it is the most often played, so we should check it. }
5... Nc6 6. Qd1
{ No matter where the queen goes we will reach the same position. } 6... exd5
7. Qxd5 Qc7
{ This is the great point behind Black's play ! There is only one game in my database that follows this line, and the situation doesn't look clear at all. Black has other options, but it appears that White is doing fine. It's difficult to analyze in much depth because there are no example games to check. I will simply show some variations and hopefully, in the next few months, some people will start playing these lines !   7...Bd6 ?!  8.g3 !  N  This is the suggestion of the engine and it seems very logical. Once the bishop moved to d6, Black would have to lose another tempo to attack the typical weak square on f2. Because of this it isn't necessary to play e3, so we can choose other kinds of development.   8.Bg5  This is the most played move, but White hasn't managed to pose Black any serious problems.  Nge7  9.Qd2  h6  10.Bxe7   10.O-O-O  hxg5  11.Qxd6  Qb6  12.e3  Be6  13.Bb5  O-O  14.Nf3  Rad8  =∞  Draw  (21)  Wickstrom, L  (2374)  - Jepson, C  (2430)  Sweden 2016  10...Qxe7  11.Rd1  Bb4  12.a3  Ba5  13.e3  Bg4  14.Be2  Rd8  15.Qc2  Rxd1+  16.Kxd1  Be6  =∞  Draw  (19)  Cardelli, G  (2440)  - Eckhardt, T  (2460)  ICCF email 2011  8...Nf6  9.Qd1  O-O  10.Bg2  Qe7  11.Nf3  Rd8  At first sight it might seem that Black should have enough compensation because he is very active, but I couldn't find a concrete way to prove this.  12.Qc2 !  Nb4  13.Qb1  Nbd5  14.Nxd5  Nxd5  15.O-O !  Qxe2  16.Re1  Qa6  17.Bg5  White seems to have a small initiative.   7...Bd7  would transpose to 5. Qa4, but Black would then allow the refutation with 9. Qb3.   7...Be6 ?!  8.Qxd8+  Rxd8  9.e3 !  We already checked this line in the introduction. }
8. Nf3
{ The most normal move. White simply continues development.   8.Qg5 ?!  This was played in the only game I found in the database, but it is a bit artificial.  Nf6  9.Nf3  Be6  10.e4  h6  11.Bf4  Qc8  12.Qb5  a6  13.Qa4  Bc5  14.Be2  O-O  15.O-O  Rd8  16.Rad1  b5  17.Rxd8+  Qxd8  18.Qc2  Qb6  19.h3  Rc8  =∞  Draw  (38)  Seris Granier Gonzales, M  (1985)  - Carrettoni, A  (2207)  ICCF email 2009. }
8... Nf6 9. Qb3
{ 9.Qd1 ?!  Bb4  10.Bd2  O-O  11.e3  Rd8  12.Qc2  Bg4 !  Black has a great initiative. For example:  13.Be2  Ne5  14.Nxe5  Bxe2  15.Kxe2  Qxe5  =+ }
9... Be6
{ This is the most logical move. I tried other moves, but they don't offer enough.   9...Bb4  10.e3  O-O  11.Bd2  Be6  12.Qa4  Rfd8  13.Be2  Bg4  14.Rc1  In this line, followed by a3, Black doesn't manage to create real threats.   9...Bc5  10.e3  O-O  11.Be2  Be6  12.Qc2 !  I don't want to give White this possibility. From c2, the queen protects the bishop on d2, in many lines. }
10. Qa4
{ 10.Qc2  This is the other possibility, and now the fun really starts !  Nb4 !?  11.Qb1  O-O-O !  I really like to make this move when it's good ! It feels as though you can do everything !  12.a3   12.e3 ?  is refuted by the simple  g6 !  and White has no way to avoid ...Bf5.  13.Nd4  Rxd4 !  14.exd4  Bf5  -+  12...Rd1+ !!  What a pleasure it is to make such a move. Simply an amazing resource.  13.Nxd1   13.Kxd1  Bb3+  14.Ke1  Nc2+  15.Qxc2  Bxc2  16.Be3  Bf5  17.Rc1  Kd8  The position is unclear but balanced, according to the engine.  13...Nc2+  14.Qxc2  Qxc2  15.Bf4  Qf5  16.Rc1+  Kd7  Black's king is in the center, but it is difficult for White to create winning threats. Black will play ...Bd6 followed by ...Rc8 and the position will be more or less equal. }
10... Bc5
{ This is usually the most active square for the bishop, in this Gambit. } 11.
e3 O-O 12. Be2 a6 13. O-O Rad8
{ This is a typical position. Black is a pawn down, but it is not so easy for White to develop. I consider this kind of position great for blitz games. I will try to go a bit deeper to make it easier to understand what is going on. }
14. Rd1
{ 14.Bd2  Ne5 !  A typical resource, now that the bishop on d2 is hanging.  15.Rfd1   15.Qc2  Ba7 !  I like this manoeuvre very much. The bishop will go to b8 and will threaten mate.  16.Rac1  Nfg4  Black plays for mate.   16...Nxf3+  This is an easy way to get compensation.  17.Bxf3  Ng4  18.Bxg4  Bxg4  =∞  White is a pawn up, but it's very difficult to make use of the extra material. If White plays e4, the bishop on a7 will put pressure on the kingside. But what else should White play ? Moreover, when Black plays ...Bb8, White should decide if he should play g3 or f4.  17.g3  Nxf3+  18.Bxf3  Ne5  =∞  Now the compensation is of a different kind. White cannot protect all the squares. f3 and d3 are weak and White has no activity. I would prefer Black in this position. It's instructive to note that, unless White wants to get into trouble, the best move, according to the engine, is the uninspiring 19. Be2...  15...b5 !  One more typical resource. Black pushes the kingside to gain some space.  16.Qf4  Bd6  17.Nxe5  Bxe5  18.Qh4  White has managed to place the queen on the kingside. Black doesn't have attacking possibilities anymore. But another kind of compensation appears. The queen on h4 doesn't coordinate well with the rest of White's pieces. It's like a soldier sent alone into battle, unable to cause any serious problems by herself. Black will simply play on the other side.  Qb8  19.Be1  b4  20.Na4  a5  =∞  Black's pieces are involved in the game, while White has no active possibilities. Despite the 0.00 computer evaluation, Black will normally prevail in a practical game.   14.a3  Na5 !?  Another possibility in this kind of position.  15.Rb1  Bb3  16.Qh4  Be7  =∞  All the Black pieces are very active and White is still struggling to get his pieces into the game. }
14... b5 { Once again, we make use of the b-pawn. } 15. Qc2 Nb4 16. Qb1 Rxd1+
17. Bxd1 Qd7
{ I like this queen move very much. Easy and effective. Black improves the position of the queen, and as a result creates some threats on the d line. Moreover, Black plans to play ...Bf5, forcing White to play e4. After that, Black's bishop on c5 will put pressure on f2. }
18. Bb3 Bf5
{ 18...Bg4 !?  Another option. White's queen is far from the defence of the king, which justifies starting an attack.  19.Ne5  Qd6  20.Nxg4  Nxg4  21.g3  Qh6  → }
19. e4 Bg6 20. Be3 { Sad, but the only way to hold the position. } 20... Bxe3
21. fxe3 Rd8 *

