1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qxd4
{ This is not the main line, but it is the most often played, so we should check it. }
5... Nc6 6. Qd1
{ No matter where the queen goes we will reach the same position. } 6... exd5
7. Qxd5 Qc7
{ This is the great point behind Black's play ! There is only one game in my database that follows this line, and the situation doesn't look clear at all. Black has other options, but it appears that White is doing fine. It's difficult to analyze in much depth because there are no example games to check. I will simply show some variations and hopefully, in the next few months, some people will start playing these lines ! }
8. Nf3 { The most normal move. White simply continues development. } 8... Nf6
9. Qb3 Be6
{ This is the most logical move. I tried other moves, but they don't offer enough. }
10. Qa4 Bc5
{ This is usually the most active square for the bishop, in this gambit. } 11.
e3 O-O 12. Be2 a6 13. O-O Rad8
{ This is a typical position. Black is a pawn down, but it is not so easy for White to develop. I consider this kind of position great for blitz games. I will try to go a bit deeper to make it easier to understand what is going on. }
14. Bd2 Ne5 { A typical resource, now that the bishop on d2 is hanging. } 15.
Qc2 Ba7
{ I like this manoeuvre very much. The bishop will go to b8 and will threaten mate. }
16. Rac1 Nfg4 { Black plays for mate. } 17. g3 Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Ne5
{ Now the compensation is of a different kind. White cannot protect all the squares. f3 and d3 are weak and White has no activity. I would prefer Black in this position. It's instructive to note that, unless White wants to get into trouble, the best move, according to the engine, is the uninspiring 19. Be2... }
