{ White tries to play the official refutation, but Black has an idea... } 8...
Na6
{ A very logical move yet almost unknown ! The idea is very simple: Black wants to play ...Nc5 and gain one more tempo on the White queen. }
9. Nf3 Nc5 10. Qc2 Rc8 11. e3 Bd6
{ I like the positional approach. Black's play seems to be much easier. Let me explain the strategy: Black castles and the queen goes to e7. Afterwards, Black tries to push the queenside pawns with a6 and b5, and the kingside as well with g6 and h5. This will force White to create some weaknesses on both flanks: namely the b3 square, if White plays a3, and White may also need to play h3, as well. White has an extra pawn, but how to make use of it ? Thanks to our good centralization we have control over the e4 square. It's clear that White needs to exchange some pieces, but we shouldn't allow it if possible. In a practical game, with short time controls, I don't believe that Blacks chances would be worse. }
12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Qe7 14. Bd2 g6 { Black is ready to play ...Bf5. } *

