{ I had the feeling that Black should have something in this position, but I failed to prove it. I could only find one variation where White needs to play extremely accurately to gain some advantage. So, objectively, White is better. }
13... Qb6 14. e3 { As I said before, the pawn on b2 is untouchable. } 14...
Rad8 { The best practical chance. } 15. Qc1
{ This is not an easy move to make ! White allows ...Na5-Nb3. } 15... Na5 16.
b4 { White has no fear ! } 16... Nb3 17. bxc5 Qxc5 18. Qb2 Nxa1 19. Qxa1 Rfe8
{ The position doesn't look so clear. White's king is still in the center and Black will probably have some activity. Unfortunately, for Black, White manages to consolidate. }
20. Be2 Rc8 21. Na2 Ne4 22. O-O Qxa3 23. Be5 Be6 24. Nc1 Qxa1 25. Bxa1 Nc3 26.
Bd3 Bc4
{ And if White doesn't have the bishop pair, I doubt he has an advantage. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Von Hennig-Schara Gambit - Black Repertoire"]
[Black "7...Nf6 8.Qd1 with 10.a3! with 20.Qb2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nf6
8. Qd1 Nc6 9. Nf3 Bc5 10. a3
{ I was very surprised when I saw the computer giving this move as the best by far. There is a point behind it, as you will see later. I must confess that this is the only place in the whole Gambit where I found some real advantage for White ! }
10... O-O 11. Bg5
{ The moves a3 and Bg5 seem a bit strange, one after another, but there is a point behind it. If Black plays ...Qb6, at some point, he doesn't really threaten ...Qxb2 because the queen, on b2, would be trapped ! }
11... h6 { Following Alekhine's ideas ! } 12. Bh4
{ This move seems to be very dangerous, in my opinion. The pawn on b2 is weak, Black has the possibility to gain more tempi with g5 and, who knows, maybe g4 as well. Black's pieces seem to be able to enter the game extremely easily... I thought Black should be ok, somehow, but I couldn't manage to find a reasonable continuation. Given this, we are probably looking at the REFUTATION OF THE GAMBIT. }
12... g5 13. Bg3
{ I had the feeling that Black should have something in this position, but I failed to prove it. I could only find one variation where White needs to play extremely accurately to gain some advantage. So, objectively, White is better. }
13... Qb6 14. e3 { As I said before, the pawn on b2 is untouchable. } 14...
Rad8 { The best practical chance. } 15. Qc1
{ This is not an easy move to make ! White allows ...Na5-Nb3. } 15... Na5 16.
b4 { White has no fear ! } 16... Nb3 17. bxc5 Qxc5 18. Qb2 Nxa1 19. Qxa1 Rfe8
{ The position doesn't look so clear. White's king is still in the center and Black will probably have some activity. Unfortunately, for Black, White manages to consolidate. }
20. Qb2
{ An impossible move to find in a practical game, I would say. The idea is to play Qb4 and exchange queens, but you really need to be cold-blooded to play such a move. }
20... Rc8 21. Nd1 Qa5+ 22. Qb4 Qxb4+ 23. axb4 Nd5 24. Nd4 Nxb4 25. h4
{ White has some edge. The pair of bishops will prove strong, at some point. Anyway, Black still has two passed pawns on the queenside, so the position is not without chances for Black. We will need to see practical examples ! }
