[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Dutch Gambits"]
[Black "The Staunton Gambit 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5 Nc6?!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. e4 fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5
{ 4.f3  d5 !  - we have already checked this. } 4... Nc6
{ This was considered to be the main line for many years, but Black needs to be really careful !   4...g6 !  - see the next analyzed game ! }
5. d5 Ne5 { This the main line, but after.... } 6. Qe2
{ ...it seems as though the gambit is going to work !   6.f4 !?  This is yet another interesting way of playing:  exf3  7.Nxf3  Nf7  8.Bc4  White seems to have a serious initiative for the pawn.   6.Qd4 ?!  This is the main line, but Black is doing fine. I really don't understand this move. It's very common in the opening to use unstable Knights on e5 to gain tempi to develop the other pieces. But simply attacking it to force the Knight into a better position is not very logical.  Nf7 !  7.Bxf6  exf6  8.O-O-O !?  A new idea, but it does not offer enough for White.   8.Nxe4  f5  9.Ng3  g6  10.O-O-O  Bh6+ !  Black will castle and have the advantage of the Bishop pair.  8...f5  9.f3  Bd6 !  A very important move to complete development !  10.fxe4   10.Qxg7 ?  Be5  The Queen is trapped !  10...Be5  11.Qd2  O-O !  Now Black is playing a gambit !  12.exf5  d6  and Black has enough compensation. The game could continue:  13.g4 !?  Qh4  14.Qg2  Bxc3  15.bxc3  Ne5  =∞ }
6... c6
{ 6...Nf7  7.Bxf6  exf6  8.Nxe4  Qe7   8...Be7  9.d6  cxd6  10.Nc3  +=  9.d6 !  Black's pawn structure is destroyed and White is better.   6...d6  7.O-O-O !  White is better because it is difficult for Black to complete the development. }
7. f4
{ A very nice idea ! This is found in the games of the talented chess player from Czech Republic, Vojtech Plat. }
7... Nf7
{ 7...exf3  8.Nxf3  Nxf3+  9.Qxf3  The White lead in development is too much. }
8. Bxf6 gxf6
{ 8...exf6 !?  N  This is probably the best try !  9.Qxe4+   9.Nxe4  looks scarier but leads to an amazing position:  Qa5+  10.Nc3+  Kd8 !  The King feels quite safe in the center !  11.O-O-O  Bb4 !  12.Qg4   12.Qf3 ?!  Bxc3  13.Qxc3  Qxc3  14.bxc3  Kc7 !  and Black has the better endgame.  12...Bxc3  13.Qxg7  Bxb2+  14.Kxb2  Qb4+  15.Ka1  Qc3+  16.Kb1  And Black should probably go for the perpetual.  9...Qe7  10.O-O-O  Qxe4  11.Nxe4  Nd6  12.Nxd6+  Bxd6  13.g3  It may be that White is slightly better in this endgame, but Black can probably hold. }
9. Qxe4
{ This was the choice of Robert Aloma Vidal, an International Master who has excellent knowledge of opening theory. At least he outplayed me, once...   9.Nxe4 ?  This was Plat's choice, but it is not correct ! Ok, I understand why it is so tempting ... maybe our opponent will overlook Nxf6 mate !  Qa5+ !   9...cxd5 ?  10.Nxf6#  10.c3 ?!   10.Nc3 !  Bh6  with a complex battle ahead.  10...cxd5 ?   10...f5 !  ∓  Black will simply win a pawn.  11.Nxf6+  Kd8  12.Qh5  ±  Plat, V - Wozniak, M. Marianske Lazne 2016, and White eventually won. }
9... e6 10. O-O-O
{ This seems to be the most accurate.   10.dxe6 !?  dxe6  11.Bc4  f5 ?!  after   11...Nd6 !  Black would be close to equality.  12.Qe2  +=  Aloma Vidal, R - Yepes Martinez, E and White eventually won. }
10... cxd5 11. Rxd5 Qe7 12. Rd1 { Leisebein, P - Klein,R DESC email 2006. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Dutch Gambits"]
[Black "The Staunton Gambit 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5 g6!"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. e4 fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 g6
{ This is a new way to fight the Staunton Gambit ! It is probably quite good because the chief expert in the Dutch, these days, is my friend David Anton, and he plays it ! }
5. Bc4
{ A very interesting move, which enjoys really good results at the amateur level ! White simply develops the pieces to the most active squares ! I think I would be willing to try this line at least once, with White !   5.h4 !?  Trying to punish the g6 move, which looks very logical.  d5  6.h5  Bf5 !  We develop our Bishop and defend g6, a multi-purpose move.  7.Bxf6  exf6  8.g4  Be6  9.hxg6  Qd7 !  David Anton has two games involving this position.  10.g5 !   10.f4 ?  Bxg4 ?!  A very easy mistake to make.   10...Qg7 !  An extremely difficult move to find, but it is very good.  11.f5 ?  hxg6 !  12.Rxh8  Qxh8  13.fxe6  Qh4+  14.Ke2  Qh2+  -+  11.Bh3 !  Bxh3  12.Rxh3  Nc6  13.Qh5  O-O-O  ∓  Alvarez Fernandez, E - Anton Guijarro, D Linares 2013, and the game was eventually drawn, but it was clear who had the upper hand.  10...fxg5  11.Qh5  Qg7 !  I was at this tournament and saw the game, live. I was particularly surprised by this move, but it is easier to find this kind of move, of course, if you played a similar game a couple of years ago. At the end of the day, hard work delivers results !   11...Bg7  was the normal move:  12.gxh7+  Qf7  13.Qxg5  Nc6  and Black has compensation.  12.Qxg5  c6 !  13.Nge2 ?!   13.f3 !  hxg6  14.Rxh8  Qxh8  15.fxe4  Be7  16.Qxg6+  Bf7  17.Qf5  Bh4+  18.Kd2  Qxd4+  19.Bd3  is balanced, according to the computer, but who would be able to play like this ?  13...hxg6  14.Nf4  Rxh1  15.Nxe6  Qh6 ?  The Dutch is difficult to play ! Even the best chess players regularly fail to find the best moves !   15...Qe7 !  16.Qxe7+  Kxe7  17.Nc7  Bg7  18.O-O-O  Kd6  19.Nxa8  Rh8 !  and Black will take the Knight on a8 with the Rook, and end up in a much better endgame.  16.Qd8+  Kf7  17.Ng5+  Kg8  18.Qf6 !  And White gets a perpetual !  Na6  19.Qe6+  Kg7  20.Qe5+  Kg8  21.Qe6+  Kg7  22.Qe5+  Kg8  23.Qe6+  - Trent, L - Anton Guijarro, D Gibraltar 2015. A truly exciting game !   5.Qe2  d5  6.f3   6.O-O-O  Nc6  7.f3  Bg7  This is similar to the main line.  6...Bg7  7.O-O-O   7.fxe4  Nc6 !  8.Bxf6  Bxf6  9.Nxd5  Nxd4  10.Nxf6+  exf6  11.Qf2  Nc6 =  7...Nc6  8.Kb1 !  This is a difficult move to make, but it will likely be useful in the future. Besides, it is not so clear how White should play, at the moment. After this, Black has two different, but interesting, moves.   8.fxe4 ?!  Nxe4  9.Nxe4  dxe4  10.Qxe4  Bf5 !  and all the Black pieces are playing. Later, Black will play Qd7 or Qd6, followed by long castle and a better game.   8.Bxf6  Bxf6  9.fxe4  Nxd4 !  =+  8...O-O   8...Bf5  9.Qe3  O-O  10.g4  Be6  Black seems to be fine here, too, but the position is a bit more unclear.  9.Qe1  White wants to develop the Bishop and play Qh4, at some point.  a6 !?  10.Bxf6  exf6  11.fxe4  dxe4  12.Qxe4  f5  with a balanced position, although I prefer to have the pair of Bishops.   5.f3  d5 !   5...exf3  6.Nxf3  Bg7  This may be fine for Black, but I'm not a fan of giving White such a great advantage in development.  6.Qd2   6.fxe4 ?!  Nxe4  7.Nxe4  dxe4  8.Bc4  Nc6 !  9.Ne2  Na5 !  and Black will have an extra pawn and the pair of Bishops.   6.Qe2  we analyzed this before in 5. Qe2  6...Bg7  7.O-O-O  Nc6 !  This puts pressure on d4. Now a forced line appears on the board.  8.Bxf6  exf6 !  9.fxe4  dxe4  10.Nxe4  Qxd4   10...f5 !?  This is a riskier way of playing.  11.Ng5  Qxd4  12.Qe1+  Qe5  13.N1f3  Qxe1  14.Rxe1+  Kf8  15.Bb5  and White has compensation, but nothing more.  11.Qxd4  Nxd4  12.Rxd4  f5  13.Rc4  fxe4  14.Rxe4+  Kd8  =+  The endgame is slightly better for Black, but not that much because the King doesn't look particularly comfortable on c8.   5.d5  Bg7  6.Bc4  This transposes to the line following 5. Bc4. }
5... c6 { The most logical move. I want to close the Bishop's diagonal. } 6. d5
{ This is the key move ! } 6... Bg7 7. Nge2
{ Simply developing pieces. Now Black has at least two options to obtain a comfortable game.   7.Qd2 ?!  Natural, but very slow.  e6 !!  This is a great positional idea.  8.d6   8.dxe6  d5 !  ∓   8.dxc6  d5  9.cxb7  Bxb7  ∓  8...b5  9.Bb3  a5  10.a3  O-O  and the pawn on d6 is completely useless because it does nothing to hinder the development of our pieces. We have b7 for the Bishop, b6 for the Queen and a6 for the Knight. Don't be afraid ! }
7... e6
{ The safest choice. This is the move I like the most.   7...b5  is a very aggressive choice. The engine assesses the position as unclear, and I believe only practice will tell us who is better !  8.Bb3  a5  9.dxc6   9.a3  This could lead to a funny draw after  a4  10.Ba2  Bb7  11.d6  e6 !  12.Nxe4  Qa5+  13.Bd2  Qb6  14.Be3  Qa5+ =  9...Nxc6   9...dxc6  10.Qxd8+  Kxd8  is fine for Black.  10.a4 !  bxa4   10...b4 ?!  11.Nb5 !  White gets an outpost for the Knight on b5, which is something to avoid.  11.Rxa4  e6  and the position is balanced. }
8. Nxe4 O-O
{ 8...cxd5 ?!  9.Bxd5 !  exd5  10.Bxf6  Bxf6  11.Qxd5 !  The computer says that the position is balanced, but in a practical game Black would probably constantly get mated. }
9. dxe6 d5 10. O-O Bxe6 11. Bb3 Nbd7
{ Black has solved all of his problems and can start thinking about fighting for the advantage. }
*

