1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3 a5 6. Nbd2
{ This is the main line in theory. } 6... Nge7 7. Nb3 Nf5 8. Bg5
{ An interesting idea for White. There are almost no games that feature this continuation. More practical examples are needed to make clear which variation is better.   8.e4  dxe3  9.Qxd8+  Nxd8  10.fxe3  This endgame is the main recommendation of the computer, but I'm not very happy about this. If White doesn't play accurately, he might end up losing the pawn on e5 and will get a worse endgame. One possible line would be:  Nc6  11.Bd2  a4  12.Nbd4  Bc5  13.Nb5  Kd8  14.e4  Ne3  15.Ke2  Nxc4  16.Bg5+  Be7  17.Kf2  N4xe5  18.Rd1+  Bd7  19.Bxe7+  Kxe7  20.Nxc7  Ra5  +=  This was the first line of my engine. I analysed more options, but it doesn't make sense to give them all. Here we are in a typical scenario for this endgame. According to the engine, White is better. The problem is that White should be careful because of the weakness on e4. If White doesn't play accurately, he can be worse ! }
8... Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nbxd4 Nfxd4
{ 10...Ncxd4 ?!  Black doesn't have enough compensation in this position.  11.Nxd4  Qxe5  12.e3  O-O  13.Nxf5  Bxf5  14.Qd4 !  Qe7   14...Qxd4  15.exd4  Rad8  16.O-O-O  Rfe8  17.b3  g6  18.Kb2  h5  19.Kc3  White won the endgame without problems in Riazantsev, A  (2646)  - Pankov, G  (2404)  Minsk 2015.  15.Be2  Rfd8  16.Qc3  ±  White was a pawn up but didn't manage to win in Khenkin, I  (2551)  - Berelowitsch, A  (2523)  Belgium 2017. }
11. Nxd4 O-O { This move has not been found, yet ! } 12. Nxc6
{ 12.e3  Rd8  13.Be2  Qc5 = } 12... bxc6 13. Qd2 Qxe5 14. O-O-O Rb8
{ The engine considers White to be better, but I'm not so happy with my King on the queenside. Black will always have some counterplay. For example: }
15. Qd4 Qe7 16. e4 c5 17. Qe3 Bd7
{ Followed by ...Ba4 and ...Rb3 in some lines. White is better, but how much, I'm not sure. }
