[Black "Gurbanov, Andrei vs. Kett, Timothy"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 e6 4. c4 b5 5. dxe6 fxe6 6. cxb5 Bb7 7. e3 d5
{ REMEMBER ! What was important in this position ? Think and, if you don't remember, you know what to do ! }
8. b3 Bd6 9. Bb2 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 Qe7 11. Qc2
{ White tried to get control of the e4 square.   11.Be2  This was the other option. We are somehow not in time for e4.  e5  12.Nh4 !  I don't like to make this kind of move, but sometimes it is necessary.   12.e4 !?  is very risky:  Nxe4  13.Nxe4  dxe4  14.Nd2  White is about to consolidate with Nc4, but Black has something to say  e3 !  A very important clearance sacrifice. Black's bishop is alive !  15.fxe3  Bxg2  16.Nc4  Bc7  17.Rg1  Qh4+  18.Kd2  O-O-O  An extremely odd position. We have equal material, but everything else is completely imbalanced ! The game could follow  19.Kc1  Be4  =+  Black is more active, the pawn is hanging on h2 and, believe it or not, Black's king is safer ! Nothing can attack it !  12...g6  13.e4  c4 !  Black should not allow White to maintain such good control of the c4 square.   13...dxe4  14.Nc4  ±  14.O-O  Nc5 !  15.bxc4  d4  =∞  One more position in the Blumenfeld spirit ! Black is two pawns down, but all the pieces are active ! Black threats to take on e4 and the knight on h4 is misplaced. The engine evaluates the position as equal, but in a practical game I think that Black would have better chances ! }
11... O-O 12. Bd3
{ 12.Be2 !?  This is the best way, according to the engine, but I don't like the position at all.  e5  13.e4   13.Nh4  g6  14.e4  c4 !  This move should not anymore be a mystery.  15.O-O  c3 !  This is what I call full activity !  16.Qxc3  Rac8  17.Qe3  Rc2 !  18.Bc1  Bc5  =∞  All the Black pieces are attacking something !  13...c4 !  14.O-O  Rac8 !  15.bxc4  Nxe4  16.Nxe4  dxe4  17.Nd2  Nc5  =∞  Once again, Black is really active. Qg5 is coming with e3 ideas. }
12... e5 13. e4 c4 { Seems like Timothy knew what he was doing ! Bravo ! } 14.
bxc4 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 Nf6 18. Qe2 Bb4+ 19. Kf1 e4 20.
Nd4 Bc5 21. Nf5
{ White made a mistake in a difficult position.   21.Kg1  was more stubborn. }
21... Qd7 22. Bxf6
{ 22.Ne3  This was probably White's idea, but after  Bxe3  23.Qxe3  Ng4  24.Qd4  Qe7  followed by Rad8 and Rxf2, White's position collapses. }
22... Qxf5 23. Bh4 g5 24. Bg3 Rad8
{ Two pawns downs but everything is active. Every Blumenfeld player wants this ! }
25. Kg1 Rd3 26. Rf1 e3 27. Rc1 Rd2 28. Qf3 Qd7
{ A great game played at an extremely high level, bearing in mind that neither were Grandmasters ! }
