[SetUp "1"]

{ Choose between two options: 17... Bb4+ or 17... Nf6. } 1... Bb4+
{ It was important to force the king to move, while he is on e1, so that he cannot later castle kingside or queenside. It would be very strange if we had resources to mate the king on both sides. This may seem obvious, but many people forget it !   17...Nf6  This was the game continuation. }
2. Kf1
{ 18.Kd1 ?  Nc5  19.Qxe5  Qf7 !  Followed by ...Rad8, and mate is coming.   18.Ke2  Nc5  19.Qd5+  Kh8  It does not look very sensible to place the king on the same line as the Black queen. }
2... Rae8
{ Preparing ...Nf6. Once again, Black improves the position before striking ! }
3. Kg1
{ Black has every piece on the best squares, so it's time to initiate active play ! }
3... Nf6 4. Qxe5 Qd7 5. Qd4 Qf5
{ Three pawns down, but all the Black pieces are active and White cannot coordinate the rooks. Black is better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games with Exercises"]
[Black "Blumenfeld Gambit Exercise 3"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/p3q1pp/5n2/1P2p3/1bP5/5N2/PB2QPPP/R3K2R w KQ - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Sorry for disturbing you, but again you have three options !   1. 19. Kd1 and then run away to c2 !   2. 19. Kf1 hoping to find safety on the kingside.   3. 19. Nd2 pinning yourself. }
1. Nd2
{ Very difficult but very good ! The queen goes to the queenside but the difference compared with Kd1 is huge for two reasons:   1. The knight on d2 will be close to help the defense.   2. The rooks are connected !   Of course, being pinned is not nice, but sometimes the bad is needed for the best !   19.Kd1  Ba3 !  An extremely difficult move to find, so let me explain the concept: we are fixing the Killing Zone, namely the queenside. Once the king goes to b2, the bishop is the only piece protecting him ! We exchange our bishop because he was pointing to the kingside, but now we are attacking the queenside and don't need him anymore !   19...e4 ?!  This would be the normal move.  20.Nd4  e3  Black has the initiative, as well, but White's position is not so easy to crack.  20.Bc3 !  I don't know of a single chess player who would be able to make such a calm move, simply controlling the b4 square. Only after a long think could anyone arrive at this move, by a process of elimination.   20.Qxe5  Qb4 !  21.Bxa3  Qxa3  ∓  20...Rac8 !  =∞  The engine evaluates the position close to equal, but it's very hard to find the best moves for White.   19.Kf1  was played in the game. }
1... Rfd8 2. O-O-O
{ The most normal move.   20.Bc1 !?  is another possibility, planning to castle kingside.  Qd7 ?   20...Bc3  21.Rb1  Rac8  22.O-O  ±  21.O-O !  Bxd2  22.Rd1  +- }
2... a6 3. Nb3
{ White has too many pieces on the queenside so mate cannot be delivered. It's good to practise calculating this kind of position. It can train you in the art of defense as well as attack ! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
