[SetUp "1"]

{ What to do as White ? I'm not offering any options, this time ! } 1. Qf3
{ The best practical move ! Sometimes, if we are up materially and defending, it's a good idea to give some material back to nullify the opponents initiative.   20.Qe2  Not bad, but not good, either. It's not a forcing move and allows two interesting possibilities.  Ne4+   20...Qg6+  21.Kh2  21.Kh2  Qxf1  22.Qxe4  Rae8  23.Qg4  h5 !  24.Qxh5  Re1  25.Qg4  Rf2 =   20.Rxf2  This is the best move according to the engine, but not so practical in my opinion.  Qxf2+  21.Kh3 !  The only move !   21.Kh2 ?  Qh4+  22.Kg1  Rae8  23.Bd2  Qf2+  24.Kh2  Re2  -+  21...Rf6 !  Black keeps his options open. ...Raf8, ...Re8 and ...Rg6, three different moves. The more options you have the more difficult it is for your opponent to defend.  22.Bd2 !  A difficult to find calm move, but there are no killing ideas, in this position, and by playing this our rook takes control of the a-file.  Qf5+  23.Qg4  Qxd5  24.Re1  +=  White is better and managed to consolidate. But you would need to find the calm 22. Bd2, if you decide to play 20. Rxf2. I guess that Riazantsev didn't see that, or maybe his intuition told him that giving the queen was safer. }
1... Qg6+ 2. Kxf2 Rxf3+ 3. gxf3
{ White is better. Two pieces and a rook, if they are well coordinated, are normally good enough to outplay a queen, in the long term. }
