{ What to do as White ?   1. 15. Bb2   2. 15. Qc2   3. 15. Nd4 } 1. Bb2
{ The best move. I know, it is difficult to leave the queen on the d-file, but this doesn't seem to be a problem here.   15.Nd4 ?!  One of the typical moves. Unfortunately, Black develops a very strong initiative.  Rac8  16.Bb2  Neg4 !  The Black pieces are working together in great fashion ! White should be careful to maintain the balance.  17.Bxg4  Nxg4  18.h3  Nh2  19.Re1  Bxh3 !  20.gxh3  Qg5+  21.Kh1  Qh4  22.Kg2 !  Qg5+  Draw !   15.Qc2  happened in the game and is not so good. }
1... Rac8 2. Rc1 { White continues playing with nerves of steel ! } 2... Nfg4
3. g3 { Now the kingside is better protected, thanks to the queen on d1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games with Exercises"]
[Black "Von Hennig-Schara Gambit Exercise 7"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2rr2k1/pp1bqppp/3b4/4n3/1P4n1/P1N1PN2/1BQ1BPPP/R4RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How to defend, 17. h3 or 17. g3 ? } 1. h3
{ How to arrange our pawns ? What a difficult question ! There are very few players in the world who usually manage to place them correctly. And here the question is not easy to answer, but let's have a closer look, as it will help us better to understand the key ideas in this kind of middlegame. In my opinion, this is the best practical chance, although it is difficult to say what is best !  Instead,   17.g3  was played in the game. }
1... Nxf3+ 2. Bxf3
{ There are three different ways to continue the attack, all of them are interesting ! }
2... Qe5
{ 18...Nh2  19.Bxb7  Rc7  20.Rfd1 !  Rxb7  21.Qe2  A very strange position. For now, White is piece down, but Blacks knight is trapped on h2, and f4 is coming. The game could continue  Bc6  22.f4  Rbd7  23.Qf2   23.Kxh2 ?  Bxf4+  24.exf4  Qxe2  25.Nxe2  Rxd1  -+  23...Nf3+  24.gxf3  Bc7  Black is two pawns down, but the white queen is very poorly placed. The engine says 0.00, but I can assure you that I would prefer Black !   18...Bh2+ !?  This is the positional approach.  19.Kh1  Bb8  Now Black wants to play ...Qd6.  20.Bxg4  Bxg4  21.Qe4 !  Of course, White tries to exchange queens.  Qxe4  22.Nxe4  Bf5  +=  White is slightly better thanks to the extra pawn, but Black has the pair of bishops and very active pieces. This should be enough for a draw. }
3. g3 Nxe3 { Of course, I didn't consider retreating ! } 4. fxe3 Bxh3 5. Qf2
Rxc3 6. Bxc3 Qxc3
{ Black is the exchange down but White's kingside is extremely damaged. The g3 pawn will suffer, in the future. Plus, Black has no weakness. So, besides the deficit in material, the position is more or less balanced. }
